{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8900e96e-7e9f-4b38-8269-869479420279","content":"Here's what you need:\n\n**Environment variables** to enable crash dumps with your custom `createdump` path:\n\n```yaml\nenv:\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump\n    value: \"1\"\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType\n    value: \"4\"                          # 1=Mini, 2=Heap, 3=Triage, 4=Full\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName\n    value: \"/tmp/dumps/core.%p.%t\"      # %p=PID, %t=timestamp\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath\n    value: \"/opt/tools/createdump\"\n```\n\n**Pod spec changes:**\n\n```yaml\nspec:\n  containers:\n    - name: your-app\n      # ... existing config ...\n      securityContext:\n        capabilities:\n          add: [\"SYS_PTRACE\"]           # required — createdump uses ptrace\n      volumeMounts:\n        - name: crash-dumps\n          mountPath: /tmp/dumps\n  volumes:\n    - name: crash-dumps\n      emptyDir:\n        sizeLimit: 4Gi                  # tune to your app's memory footprint\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`SYS_PTRACE`** is mandatory — `createdump` attaches via `ptrace` to snapshot the crashing process. Without it, dump collection silently fails.\n- **`DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath`** is needed since your `createdump` isn't in the default SDK location.\n- **Dump type 4 (Full)** gives the most debugging info but produces the largest files. Use `1` (Mini) if storage is tight.\n- Use a **persistent volume** instead of `emptyDir` if you need dumps to survive pod restarts. With `emptyDir`, retrieve dumps via `kubectl cp` or a sidecar before the pod terminates.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"771b03d7-fc52-43e6-999c-415c4c4b8380","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to configure automatic crash dump collection for a NativeAOT .NET 11 app running in Kubernetes. They have `createdump` installed at `/opt/tools/createdump`.\n\nFor .NET NativeAOT apps, crash dump collection works differently than regular CoreCLR apps. Let me provide the environment variables and pod spec changes needed.\n\nKey considerations:\n1. NativeAOT apps don't use the same `COMPlus_*` or `DOTNET_*` environment variables for crash dumps as CoreCLR apps do.\n2. For NativeAOT, crash dump generation needs to be configured differently - typically via the `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName` and `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump` environment variables, but these may not work with NativeAOT.\n\n\n3. Actually, starting with .NET 7+, NativeAOT does support crash dumps through environment variables like `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1` to enable collection, `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType` to specify the dump type (mini, heap, triage, or full), `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName` for the output path pattern, and `DOTNET_CreateDumpDiagnostics` to enable diagnostics for the createdump tool.\n\nFor .NET 8+ specifically, I need to set `DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath` to point to the createdump tool at its custom location, and in Kubernetes I'll need to configure additional settings to ensure the dumps are properly captured and accessible.","outputTokens":1202},"id":"2d4189f5-0571-4267-b86d-6d47afd5b6be","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:59:55.335Z","parentId":"d4e49a8e-94cf-442d-915e-30fd4f0a19d0"}
